{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488568","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488568"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:47:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:47:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"480"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"480","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/480"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.02,0.71,0.02,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"480"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82737"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"480","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/480"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"480"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67872"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"238"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1787"},{"type":"tags","id":"2702"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1899"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2315"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82737","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82737"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of progressive shortness of breath on exertion and a non-productive cough. She has no chest pain. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She is a lifetime non-smoker and reports no recent travel or sick contacts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Her BMI is 26 kg/m2. Fine, bilateral basal crackles are heard on chest auscultation. The remainder of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe GP refers the patient for pulmonary function tests to confirm their suspected diagnosis. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following pulmonary function test results would most strongly support the diagnosis of idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reduced FEV1/FVC ratio","Increased lung compliance","Decreased total lung capacity","Normal diffusion capacity","Increased residual volume"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis (IPF): progressive exertional dyspnoea, dry cough, and fine bibasal crackles on auscultation. The key pulmonary function test finding in IPF is a restrictive pattern.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased total lung capacity\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of restrictive lung diseases like IPF. The fibrotic process reduces lung volumes while maintaining normal airflow, resulting in proportionally reduced FEV1 and FVC with a preserved ratio.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduced FEV1/FVC ratio\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of obstructive lung diseases like asthma or chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, where airflow is limited but lung volumes may be normal or increased.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased lung compliance\u003C/strong\u003E is seen in emphysema where the elastic recoil of the lungs is reduced. IPF causes reduced lung compliance due to fibrosis making the lungs stiff and less distensible.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal diffusion capacity\u003C/strong\u003E would be unusual in IPF. The diffusion capacity (DLCO) is typically reduced due to thickening of the alveolar-capillary membrane by the fibrotic process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased residual volume\u003C/strong\u003E is seen in obstructive lung diseases where air trapping occurs. In IPF, all lung volumes including residual volume are reduced due to the restrictive process.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis (IPF) is characterised by decreased total lung capacity, decreased DLCO, and preserved FEV1/FVC ratio on pulmonary function testing.","Fine, bibasal \u0027velcro-like\u0027 crackles on auscultation are a characteristic early finding in IPF.","Progressive exertional dyspnoea and dry cough are the typical presenting symptoms of IPF."],"references":["Richeldi L, Collard HR, Jones MG. Idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis. Lancet 2017; 389: 1941\u201352","Martinez FJ, Collard HR, Pardo A, et al. Idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2017;3:17074. Published 2017 Oct 20. doi:10.1038/nrdp.2017.74"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67872"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"480"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67872","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67872"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-30T22:02:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-30T22:02:13+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"480"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82737"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta"